<p>France stepped back from the brink on Thursday as Prime Minister Sébastien Lecornu survived two no-confidence votes, easing a political crisis and averting a government collapse [france24.com#1][abcnews.go.com#1]. The reprieve followed his proposal to temporarily suspend the contested 2023 pension reform, a move aimed at securing space to govern and advance the budget [dawn.com#1][lemonde.fr#1]. While the failed votes give President Emmanuel Macron breathing room before a tough budget fight, opponents signaled further challenges that could complicate fiscal plans [france24.com#1][foreignpolicy.com#1]. Overall, the result preserves stability for now, with a constructive window to negotiate the public finances [abcnews.go.com#1][france24.com#1].</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/GpPn3FCvkY0AfO8dFUJ0aDY9sykpYS0hcxCRF0vdRUfZ8SzOhLF0JiHqf3jv8lKR3HhA10TPBCPT3HKHFvxX6DPAlxPqztHASXwXRaLTLgoM' alt='Prime Minister Sébastien Lecornu speaks with National Assembly President Yaël Braun-Pivet after the no-confidence vote results in Paris on October 16.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Budget timeline: Parliamentary negotiations on the budget are due to start next week, with the government seeking to pass an austerity package by year’s end [dawn.com#1].</li><li>Motion sponsors: The failed censure attempts were filed separately by France Unbowed on the left and the National Rally on the right [dawn.com#1].</li><li>Fresh cabinet: The votes occurred just days after Lecornu appointed his new government [dawn.com#1].</li><li>Political arithmetic: Macron’s camp lacks an absolute majority after last year’s snap elections, making cross-party bargaining essential for any budget deal [dawn.com#1][foreignpolicy.com#1].</li></ul><blockquote>If the government does not honour its commitments, particularly regarding the suspension of the pension reform, we would immediately vote against the cabinet - Olivier Faure</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Government (Sébastien Lecornu): Signaled readiness to work on budget negotiations immediately after the votes. (<a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1949447/french-pm-survives-two-no-confidence-votes'>Dawn</a>)</li><li>Socialist Party (PS): Warned it could still back a move to topple the government if the promised pension suspension is not delivered. (<a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1949447/french-pm-survives-two-no-confidence-votes'>Dawn</a>)</li><li>Policy analysts: Argue that bargaining over pension reform may still fall short of securing enough votes to pass the budget. (<a href='https://foreignpolicy.com/2025/10/16/france-lecornu-no-confidence-votes-budget-socialists-pension-reform-macron/'>Foreign Policy</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.france24.com/en/video/20251017-french-pm-lecornu-survives-no-confidence-vote-easing-political-crisis-for-now'>French PM Lecornu survives no confidence vote, easing political crisis for now</a> - france24.com</li><li><a href='https://japantoday.com/category/world/france-steps-back-from-the-brink-as-parliament-spares-the-prime-minister.-for-now'>France steps back from the brink as parliament spares the prime minister. For now</a> - japantoday.com</li><li><a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1949447/french-pm-survives-two-no-confidence-votes'>French PM survives two  no-confidence votes</a> - dawn.com</li><li><a href='https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/france-steps-back-brink-parliament-spares-prime-minister-126580500'>Political crisis in France eases for now as prime minister survives no-confidence vote</a> - abcnews.go.com</li><li><a href='https://foreignpolicy.com/2025/10/16/france-lecornu-no-confidence-votes-budget-socialists-pension-reform-macron/'>Lecornu Survives Two No-Confidence Votes—at a Price</a> - foreignpolicy.com</li><li><a href='https://www.lemonde.fr/en/les-decodeurs/article/2025/10/17/what-does-a-suspension-of-france-s-pension-reform-actually-mean_6746512_8.html'>What does a &#x27;suspension&#x27; of Fran